node.text:
💖 The cost of not following your heart is spending the rest of your life wishing you had 💖 It took me almost 2 years to discover my life purpose, and I am still shaping and evolving the idea. And of course trying to do something with this deep personal analysis of what I love. 
I really believe we attract the right things when we have a sense of who we are. Following those important things give our lives meaning and happiness. 
If you are asking ... How to start? Think about what you’re passionate about, things you love to do, what you’re good at. If you need help, ask your friends, colleagues or family these 3 questions:

1) What do you think I am good at, and I do really well?

2) What do I never shut up about / am passionate about?

3) What do I help you do that perhaps I don't realize?

Our purpose should be the main driving force of our life. Let's try to know ourselves better. 

If you are an entrepreneur, at @thecuriousbeetle we've created an eBook that I believe it will help you. "How to find the purpose of your brand" is written in English and Spanish. Link in Bio.

node.text:
Me vine a Madrid, en busca de sol, calor, familia, comida rica y descanso. 

Les cuento que sigo con mí dolor de garganta crónico... Ya van 18 meses. He probado de toooodo. Ni se imaginan la variedad de tratamientos que he intentado. Tradicionales y no tradicionales. No tengo un diagnóstico claro y eso es lo que no ayuda a mí cabecita controladora que le gusta los rótulos.

Seguiré los consejos de mí hermana Vanessa, (es la que vive en Madrid), dejaré de pelear contra el dolor y me entregaré a él y ver que tiene para enseñarme.  Ya hice una lista larga de todo lo que estoy decodificando me está queriendo decir. 

📷 @iansnowltd

node.text:
I found these handwoven Songkets 3 years ago in a Sasak Village in Lombok Island, Indonesia. My husband Pranav came with me. We hired a motorbike in Kuta and drove around 30 minutes until we arrived there. An amazing adventure. 🤠

Songkets are exquisite textiles from Malay culture. I was lucky to find 3 of these unique pieces in Indonesia. And they are ON SALE‼️⁣ I hope you’ll take a bit of this wonderful trip home with you. 🙏
 
I bought these beautiful textiles to a lovely woman: Inaq Ayat - you can see a picture of her in this carousel. I fell in love with the gorgeous colours and designs of her Songkets. At plain sight, you could see there was extremely complex work behind them . 🧵🪡
 ⁣
Songkets are done in two stages:⁣
𝟏- Weaving of the background cloth, usually done in cotton or silk.⁣
𝟐- Embroidering motifs with coloured, gold or silver threads, creating a shimmering effect. ✨⁣
 ⁣
In the kingdom age, Songkets were considered 𝘱𝘳𝘦𝘴𝘵𝘪𝘨𝘪𝘰𝘶𝘴 𝘵𝘦𝘹𝘵𝘪𝘭𝘦𝘴. They were only worn by royal Malay families during ceremonial occasions. 👑 Nowadays, it is a required garment for traditional ceremonies and weddings.⁣ ❤️
 ⁣
There’s nothing more inspiring than meaningful stories behind beautiful crafts. Songkets can be used as bedspreads, tablecloths, wall hangings… Or anything you can imagine! They can even be used as exotic fabrics for boho clothes or accessories. 😉
 ⁣
Remember, this is a 𝐅𝐋𝐀𝐒𝐇 𝐒𝐀𝐋𝐄 and there are 𝐎𝐍𝐋𝐘 𝟑 𝐒𝐎𝐍𝐆𝐊𝐄𝐓𝐒 𝐋𝐄𝐅𝐓! Send me a DM if you want these amazing textiles to be the spectacle of your home decoration!⁣
⁣
Shipping 𝗪𝐎𝐑𝐋𝐃𝗪𝐈𝐃𝐄! 🌎
⁣
Measurements: A set of two pieces 190 x 52 cm each piece approximately. Total Set: 190 x 104 cm for only 99 USD.

node.text:
“Marry a clear intention with an elevated emotion and get ready. Something unusual will happen in your life.” 

So says @drjoedispenza my meditation guru, whose words are guiding me to become the person I want to be. 🙏🤍

For quite some time, I longed for a new, exciting, and fulfilling experience in my life that would connect with my mission: helping the world become a better place. Following Dr. Dispenza’s approach, my intention was very clear. I wanted to work for the @unitednations 

In meditation, I connected this intention with elevated emotions: feeling motivated, inspired, in love with life and, most important of all, grateful. When you are thankful for something, it means it has already happened. 

And guess what? It did. 😊

I’ve worked on three projects for the International Trade Centre @internationaltradecentre, which is the joint agency of the World Trade Organization and the United Nations, training small sustainable businesses in 11 countries. ❤️🌍

This month I’ve finished a rewarding cycle, training 10 mentors from Kenia and Perú that will guide 60 sustainable, positive-impact businesses to become prominent Change Agents. 🕊️

I’m bursting with joy and gratitude. The power of creation we harbour inside is infinite. 🙌🏼

“Remind yourself every day of who you want to be, and you’ll fire new circuits in your brain that will build the foundation of who you will become.” ✨

I’m curious 🤔 What is the intention that you want to bring to life?

node.text:
Ikats are on the verge of extinction due to modern industry. They are often exposed in museums, but i’ve got 6 OF THEM ON SALE‼️ ⁣

I’ve already separated one for myself, of course. 😂

I was shocked by the production process of Ikats. The figures in the textiles are made from a complex dyeing technique, yarn by yarn, and then composed all together.😍

Yarns are coloured with natural pigments 𝘣𝘦𝘧𝘰𝘳𝘦 the weaving with a method similar to tie-dying. Finally, they are woven into amazing textiles, showing meaningful patterns, symbols, and motifs. For me, it is magical. And for Indonesians too. ✨
 ⁣
Ikat-making is passed down by women from generation to generation, and is associated with supernatural powers: 

▪️𝐑𝐄𝐃 colour is achieved with Morinda, a sacred plant used for important ceremonies such as weddings. ❤️

◾𝐈𝐍𝐃𝐈𝐆𝐎 colour is achieved with Kombu, a type of algae that is used for protection. 💙
⁣
Warning! According to Indonesians, if the sacred pigments are not prepared traditionally, it will result in the suffering of health and wealth. 
 ⁣
Have you heard about Ikats before? They’re a perfect fit for wall hanging, upholstery, a sofa cover, or bedspread. Their deep colours combine beautifully with light shades and other patterns.⁣

However, I’m leaving these 220 cm long x 88 cm wide  approx 𝐒𝐮𝐦𝐛𝐚 𝐈𝐬𝐥𝐚𝐧𝐝 𝐈𝐤𝐚𝐭𝐬 at just 𝟏4𝟗 𝐔𝐒𝐃! Remember, there are only 6 of them left. Send me a DM before they sell out! Go to my stories to see one by one.
